---
import SiteLayout from "../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";

export const meta = {
  title: "SPY Expense Ratio vs VOO: Dividend & Cost Analysis",
  description: "Are you overpaying for the S&P 500? We break down the exact expense ratios and dividend histories of SPY and VOO to reveal the long-term winner.",
  category: "study",
  published: "2026-03-15",
};

const schema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": ["Article", "FAQPage"],
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is the SPY expense ratio vs VOO?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "The SPY expense ratio is 0.09% ($9 per $10,000 invested annually), while the VOO expense ratio is much lower at 0.03% ($3 per $10,000 invested annually)."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Does SPY pay a higher dividend than VOO?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Historically, SPY and VOO pay virtually identical dividend yields (currently around 1.35%), as they track the exact same index. However, VOO often slightly edges out SPY in total return due to its lower expense ratio."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Why is SPY's expense ratio higher than VOO?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "SPY is the oldest ETF, established in 1993, and is structured as a Unit Investment Trust (UIT). It remains the most liquid ETF for institutional traders and options volume, allowing State Street to charge a premium compared to Vanguard's VOO."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Should a long-term investor choose SPY or VOO?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "For a buy-and-hold long-term investor, VOO is mathematically superior due to its lower expense ratio (0.03%). SPY is better suited for day traders or active options traders who require maximum liquidity."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Can you reinvest dividends in SPY?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Because SPY is structured as a UIT, it cannot automatically reinvest cash dividends from its underlying holdings back into the market between dividend payment dates. This causes a slight 'cash drag' compared to VOO."
      }
    }
  ]
};
---

<SiteLayout site="westmount" title={meta.title} description={meta.description} canonical="https://westmountfundamentals.com/spy-expense-ratio-vs-voo" schema={schema}>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>SPY vs VOO: Expense Ratio & Dividend Analysis</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">Comparing the costs, yields, and structures of the two largest S&P 500 ETFs.</p>
    </div>

    <section class="content-section">
      <p>When investing in the S&P 500, the two titans dominating the conversation are State Street's <strong>SPDR S&P 500 ETF Trust (SPY)</strong> and Vanguard's <strong>S&P 500 ETF (VOO)</strong>. While both track the exact same 500 largest U.S. companies, their structural differences lead to a highly debated topic: the <strong>SPY expense ratio vs VOO</strong>. Is the oldest, most famous ETF truly the best, or does Vanguard win the war on fees and long-term yield?</p>

      <h2>Current Dividend Yield and Cost Breakdown</h2>
      <p>Because they hold the identical basket of stocks, their underlying dividend generation is practically identical. The true difference lies in the fees extracted before that cash reaches your brokerage account.</p>

      <div class="stats-grid">
        <div class="stat-card">
          <h3>SPY Expense Ratio</h3>
          <p class="calc-result-value">0.09%</p>
          <span class="badge neutral">$9 per $10k</span>
        </div>
        <div class="stat-card">
          <h3>VOO Expense Ratio</h3>
          <p class="calc-result-value">0.03%</p>
          <span class="badge positive">$3 per $10k</span>
        </div>
        <div class="stat-card">
          <h3>Current SPY Yield</h3>
          <p class="calc-result-value">1.35%</p>
          <span class="badge neutral">Quarterly</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>Currently, the SPY expense ratio sits at 0.09%, which is three times higher than the VOO expense ratio of 0.03%. Both ETFs currently offer a dividend yield around the 1.35% to 1.36% mark.</p>

      <h2>5-Year Dividend History</h2>
      <p>Since both track the broad S&P 500, their historical dividend growth reliably maps the earnings growth of America's largest corporations. The absolute dollar amounts differ simply because the share prices are fundamentally different (SPY trades at roughly 10% of the S&P 500 index value, while VOO uses a different divisor).</p>

      <div class="table-container">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Year</th>
              <th>SPY Annual Dividend</th>
              <th>VOO Annual Dividend</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>2024</td>
              <td>$7.02</td>
              <td>$6.44</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>2023</td>
              <td>$6.51</td>
              <td>$5.99</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>2022</td>
              <td>$6.32</td>
              <td>$5.82</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>2021</td>
              <td>$5.71</td>
              <td>$5.26</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>2020</td>
              <td>$5.70</td>
              <td>$5.25</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <h2>Dividend Drag and the UIT Structure</h2>
      <p>The core difference isn't just the <strong>expense ratio</strong>. SPY is structured as a Unit Investment Trust (UIT). Legally, a UIT cannot immediately reinvest cash dividends received from its underlying companies back into the market; it must hold the cash until its quarterly distribution date. In a roaring bull market, this 'cash drag' slightly reduces SPY's performance compared to VOO, which operates as a standard open-ended management company and can fully reinvest immediately.</p>

      <h2>Comparison to Category Average</h2>
      <p>Compared to the broader <a href="/average-etf-expense-ratio-2026">average ETF expense ratio</a> (around 0.37% for actively managed funds), both SPY and VOO are incredibly cheap. They dominate the <a href="/best-sp500-index-funds-2026">best S&P 500 index funds</a> category. However, SPY's higher volume and unmatched options liquidity make it the definitive choice for active day traders, while VOO is unequivocally the correct choice for long-term, buy-and-hold retail investors.</p>

      <h2>Key Metrics and Fundamentals</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>SPY AUM:</strong> > $500 Billion (The largest ETF in the world).</li>
        <li><strong>VOO AUM:</strong> Rapidly catching SPY due to 401k inflows and retail preference.</li>
        <li><strong>Strategy:</strong> Both provide near-perfect exposure to the broader U.S. economy, heavily weighted by <a href="/magnificent-seven-stocks-2026">Big Tech</a>.</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="calculator-card">
        <h3>SPY vs VOO Dividend Income Calculator</h3>
        <p>Estimate the projected annual income from your ETF holdings based on current trailing payouts.</p>

        <div class="input-group">
          <label for="shares">Shares Owned</label>
          <div class="input-wrapper">
            <input type="number" id="shares" value="100" min="1" step="1">
            <span class="suffix">shares</span>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="input-group">
          <label for="tickerSelect">Select ETF</label>
          <select id="tickerSelect" style="width: 100%; padding: 0.75rem; border-radius: 8px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); background: var(--bg-color); color: var(--text-primary); font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 1.1rem;">
            <option value="7.02">SPY ($7.02/yr)</option>
            <option value="6.44">VOO ($6.44/yr)</option>
          </select>
        </div>

        <div class="calc-result">
          <span class="calc-result-label">Projected Annual Income</span>
          <div class="calc-result-value" id="projectedIncome">$702.00</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <section class="faq-section">
        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

        <details>
          <summary>What is the SPY expense ratio vs VOO?</summary>
          <p>The SPY expense ratio is 0.09% ($9 per $10,000 invested annually), while the VOO expense ratio is much lower at 0.03% ($3 per $10,000 invested annually).</p>
        </details>

        <details>
          <summary>Does SPY pay a higher dividend than VOO?</summary>
          <p>Historically, SPY and VOO pay virtually identical dividend yields (currently around 1.35%), as they track the exact same index. However, VOO often slightly edges out SPY in total return due to its lower expense ratio.</p>
        </details>

        <details>
          <summary>Why is SPY's expense ratio higher than VOO?</summary>
          <p>SPY is the oldest ETF, established in 1993, and is structured as a Unit Investment Trust (UIT). It remains the most liquid ETF for institutional traders and options volume, allowing State Street to charge a premium compared to Vanguard's VOO.</p>
        </details>

        <details>
          <summary>Should a long-term investor choose SPY or VOO?</summary>
          <p>For a buy-and-hold long-term investor, VOO is mathematically superior due to its lower expense ratio (0.03%). SPY is better suited for day traders or active options traders who require maximum liquidity.</p>
        </details>

        <details>
          <summary>Can you reinvest dividends in SPY?</summary>
          <p>Because SPY is structured as a UIT, it cannot automatically reinvest cash dividends from its underlying holdings back into the market between dividend payment dates. This causes a slight "cash drag" compared to VOO.</p>
        </details>
      </section>
    </section>
  </div>
  <script is:inline>
    function initSPYvsVOOCalculator() {
      const container = document.querySelector('.calculator-card');
      if (!container || container.dataset.initialized === 'true') return;

      const sharesInput = document.getElementById('shares');
      const tickerSelect = document.getElementById('tickerSelect');
      const projectedIncome = document.getElementById('projectedIncome');

      function updateCalculator() {
        const shares = parseFloat(sharesInput.value) || 0;
        const dps = parseFloat(tickerSelect.value) || 0;

        const income = shares * dps;
        projectedIncome.textContent = `$${income.toFixed(2)}`;
      }

      sharesInput.addEventListener('input', updateCalculator);
      tickerSelect.addEventListener('change', updateCalculator);

      container.dataset.initialized = 'true';
    }

    document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', initSPYvsVOOCalculator);
    document.addEventListener('astro:page-load', initSPYvsVOOCalculator);
  </script>
  <style is:inline>
    .page-content { max-width: 900px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 2rem 1.5rem; }
    .hero { text-align: center; padding: 3rem 0 2rem; }
    .hero h1 { font-size: 2.2rem; font-weight: 800; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; color: var(--accent-color); }
    .subtitle { color: var(--text-secondary); font-size: 1.1rem; }
    .content-section { margin-top: 2rem; }
    .stats-grid { display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(200px, 1fr)); gap: 1.5rem; margin: 2rem 0; }
    .stat-card { background: var(--card-bg); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 12px; padding: 1.5rem; text-align: center; }
    .stat-card h3 { font-size: 1.1rem; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; color: var(--text-secondary); }
    .calc-result-value { font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 2rem; font-weight: 800; color: var(--accent-color); margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
    .badge { display: inline-block; padding: 0.25rem 0.75rem; font-size: 0.85rem; font-weight: 600; border-radius: 9999px; font-family: var(--font-mono); }
    .badge.positive { background-color: rgba(34, 197, 94, 0.1); color: #22c55e; }
    .badge.neutral { background-color: rgba(148, 163, 184, 0.1); color: var(--text-secondary); }
    .table-container { overflow-x: auto; margin: 2rem 0; }
    table { width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; background: var(--card-bg); border-radius: 12px; overflow: hidden; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); }
    th, td { padding: 1rem; text-align: left; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-color); }
    th { background-color: rgba(74, 143, 231, 0.05); color: var(--accent-color); font-weight: 600; text-transform: uppercase; font-size: 0.85rem; }
    td { color: var(--text-secondary); font-family: var(--font-mono); }
    tr:last-child td { border-bottom: none; }
    .calculator-card { background: var(--card-bg); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 12px; padding: 2rem; margin: 2.5rem 0; box-shadow: 0 4px 6px -1px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1); }
    .calculator-card h3 { text-align: center; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
    .calculator-card p { text-align: center; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; }
    .input-group { margin-bottom: 1.5rem; }
    .input-group label { display: block; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; font-weight: 600; }
    .input-wrapper { position: relative; display: flex; align-items: center; }
    .input-wrapper input { width: 100%; background: var(--bg-color); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); color: var(--text-primary); font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 1.1rem; padding: 0.75rem 1rem; border-radius: 8px; }
    .input-wrapper input:focus, select:focus { outline: none; border-color: var(--accent-color); }
    .suffix { position: absolute; right: 1rem; color: var(--text-secondary); font-family: var(--font-mono); pointer-events: none; }
    .calc-result { margin-top: 2rem; padding-top: 1.5rem; border-top: 1px solid var(--border-color); text-align: center; }
    .calc-result-label { color: var(--text-secondary); font-size: 0.95rem; display: block; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
    .faq-section { margin-top: 3rem; }
    .faq-section details { margin: 1rem 0; padding: 1.25rem; background: var(--card-bg); border-radius: 8px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); }
    .faq-section summary { font-weight: 600; cursor: pointer; font-size: 1.1rem; color: var(--text-primary); }
    .faq-section details p { margin-top: 1rem; margin-bottom: 0; }
  </style>
</SiteLayout>
